The '''Arabs''' (singular '''Arab''' {{IPAc-en|ˈ|ær|.|ə|b|UK=}};&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book |url=https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english/arab |title=Cambridge English Dictionary |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |location=UK |chapter=Arab}}&lt;/ref&gt; singular {{lang-ar|عَرَبِيٌّ}}, &lt;small&gt;[[DIN 31635]]:&lt;/small&gt; {{transliteration|ar|DIN|arabīyun}}, {{IPA-ar|ˈʕarabiːjun}}, plural {{lang-ar|عَرَب}}, [[DIN 31635|&lt;small&gt;DIN 31635&lt;/small&gt;]]&lt;small&gt;:&lt;/small&gt; {{transliteration|ar|DIN|ʿarab}}, &lt;small&gt;Arabic pronunciation:&lt;/small&gt; {{IPA-ar|ˈʕarab||Arabspronouncedar.oog.ogg}}), also known as the '''Arab people''', are an [[ethnic group]]{{efn|Sources stating Arabs are an ethnic group:&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book |last=Hitti |first=Philip K. |title=The Arabs : a short history |date=1996 |publisher=Regnery Pub. |isbn=0895267063 |location=Washington, D.C.}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book |last=Rogan |first=Eugene |title=The Arabs : a history |date=2011 |publisher=Basic Books |isbn=978-0465025046 |edition=1st pbk. |location=New York, NY}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite journal |last=F. |first=Eickelman, Dale |date=September 2013 |title=Arabs (anthropology) |url=http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopaedia-of-islam-3/arabs-anthropology-COM_24947?s.num=0&amp;s.q |journal=Encyclopaedia of Islam, Three |language=en}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book |last=Shoup |first=John A. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SPBfnT_E1mgC |title=Ethnic Groups of Africa and the Middle East: An Encyclopedia |date=31 October 2011 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=9781598843620 |language=en}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book |last=Shoup |first=John A. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SPBfnT_E1mgC&amp;pg=PA16 |title=Ethnic Groups of Africa and the Middle East: An Encyclopedia |date=31 October 2011 |isbn=9781598843620 |access-date=26 May 2014}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book |last=Barakat |first=Halim |title=The Arab world society, culture, and state |date=1993 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=0520914422 |location=Berkeley}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book |last=Reynolds |first=Dwight F. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ifcGBwAAQBAJ |title=The Cambridge Companion to Modern Arab Culture |date=2 April 2015 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=9780521898072 |language=en}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book |last=Jandt |first=Fred E. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JPb-tb_RmGEC |title=An Introduction to Intercultural Communication: Identities in a Global Community |date=2 February 2012 |publisher=SAGE Publications |isbn=9781412992879 |language=en}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web |title=ʿARAB – Encyclopaedia Iranica |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/arab-index |website=www.iranicaonline.org |language=en}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web |date=28 October 2009 |title=Arabs – MSN Encarta |url=http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761565848/Arabs.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091028022141/http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761565848/Arabs.html |archive-date=28 October 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;}} mainly inhabiting the [[Arab world]] in [[Western Asia]], [[North Africa]], the [[Horn of Africa]], and the western [[List of islands in the Indian Ocean|Indian Ocean islands]] (including the [[Comoros]]).&lt;ref name=&quot;:02&quot;&gt;{{Cite book |title=Music and media in the Arab world |date=2010 |publisher=The American University in Cairo Press |isbn=978-9774162930 |editor-last=Frishkopf |editor-first=Michael |edition=1st |location=Cairo}}&lt;/ref&gt; An [[Arab diaspora]] is also present around the world in significant numbers, most notably in the [[Americas]], [[Western Europe]], [[Arabs in Turkey|Turkey]], [[Arab Indonesians|Indonesia]], and [[Iranian Arabs|Iran]].&lt;ref name=&quot;:0b&quot;&gt;{{Cite book |title=Music and media in the Arab world |date=2010 |publisher=The American University in Cairo Press |isbn=978-977-416-293-0 |editor-last=Frishkopf |editor-first=Michael |edition=1st |location=Cairo}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book |last=Bureš |first=Jaroslav |title=Main characteristic and development trends of migration in the Arab world |date=2008 |publisher=Institute of International Relations |isbn=978-80-86506-71-5 |location=Prague}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Arab People&quot;&gt;{{Cite web |title=Arab (People) |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Arab |access-date=19 December 2020 |website=Britannica}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book |last=Bureš |first=Jaroslav |title=Main characteristic and development trends of migration in the Arab world |date=2008 |publisher=Institute of International Relations |isbn=978-8086506715 |location=Prague}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book |title=Nationalism, Language, and Muslim Exceptionalism |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |year=2015 |location=Philadelphia |pages=53–85 |chapter=4. Modern Standard Arabs |doi=10.9783/9780812291018.53}}&lt;/ref&gt; In modern usage, the term &quot;Arab&quot; tends to refer to those who both [[Arab identity|carry that ethnic identity]] and speak [[Arabic]] as their native language. This contrasts with the narrower traditional definition, which refers to the descendants of the [[tribes of Arabia]].&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book |last=Mabry |first=Tristan James |url=https://www.upenn.edu/pennpress/book/15372.html |title=Nationalism, Language, and Muslim Exceptionalism |date=2015 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania |isbn=9780812246919 |pages=53–85 |access-date=23 May 2021}}&lt;/ref&gt; The religion of [[Islam]] was developed in Arabia, and [[Classical Arabic]] serves as the language of [[Islamic literature]]. 93 percent of Arabs are [[Muslims]],&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web |date=21 April 2018 |title=Arabs facts, information, pictures |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/social-sciences-and-law/anthropology-and-archaeology/people/arabs |access-date=9 May 2018 |website=Encyclopedia.com articles about Arabs}}&lt;/ref&gt; comprising only 20 percent of the global Muslim population,&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web |title=Demographics of Islam |url=https://berkleycenter.georgetown.edu/essays/demographics-of-islam |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201009120840/https://berkleycenter.georgetown.edu/essays/demographics-of-islam |archive-date=9 October 2020 |access-date=28 September 2020}}&lt;/ref&gt; with [[Arab Christians]] comprising much of the remainder.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite journal|url=https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/full/10.1177/0265378812439955|doi = 10.1177/0265378812439955|title = Christians in the Middle East – Past, Present and Future|year = 2012|last1 = Chapman|first1 = Colin|journal = Transformation: An International Journal of Holistic Mission Studies|volume = 29|issue = 2|pages = 91–110|s2cid = 145722860}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The first mention of Arabs appeared in the mid-9th century BCE, as a tribal people in eastern and southern [[Syria (region)|Syria]] and the northern [[Arabian Peninsula]].&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book |last=Myers |first=E. A. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-cRrGQ8bIAkC |title=The Ituraeans and the Roman Near East: Reassessing the Sources |date=11 February 2010 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-1-139-48481-7 |page=18}}&lt;/ref&gt; The Arabs appear to have been under the vassalage of the [[Neo-Assyrian Empire]], as well as the succeeding [[Neo-Babylonian Empire|Neo-Babylonian]], [[Achaemenid Empire|Achaemenid]], [[Seleucid Empire|Seleucid]], and [[Parthian Empire|Parthian]] empires.&lt;ref&gt;*{{cite book|last1=Bowman|first1=Alan K.|last2=Champlin|first2=Edward|last3=Lintott|first3=Andrew|title=The Cambridge Ancient History|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-26430-3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JZLW4-wba7UC|language=en|date=8 February 1996}}
*{{cite journal|last1=Jan|first1=Retsö|title=Arabs (historical)|journal=Encyclopaedia of Islam, Three|date=October 2010|url=http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopaedia-of-islam-3/arabs-historical-COM_22957?s.num=41&amp;s.rows=50&amp;s.start=40|language=en}}
*{{Cite web |title=The origin of the word &quot;Arab&quot; |url=http://www.ismaili.net/histoire/history03/history302.html |access-date=18 December 2017 |website=Ismaili.net}}&lt;/ref&gt; The [[Nabataeans]], an Arab people, ruled a kingdom near [[Petra]] (modern-day [[Jordan]]) in the 3rd century BCE. Arab tribes, most notably the [[Ghassanids]] and the [[Lakhmids]], began to appear in the southern [[Syrian Desert]] from the mid-3rd century CE onward, during the middle to later stages of the [[Roman Empire|Roman]] and [[Sasanian Empire|Sassanid]] empires.&lt;ref&gt;* [[G. W. Bowersock|Bowersock, G. W.]], [[Peter Brown (historian)|Peter Brown]] and [[Oleg Grabar]], eds. 1999. [[iarchive:lateantiquitygui00bowe|Late Antiquity: A Guide to the Postclassical World]] (2nd ed.). Cambridge, MA: [[Belknap Press]]. {{ISBN|978-0-674-51173-6}}.
* {{cite book|last1=Cameron|first1=Averil|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_NSoAgAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PR7|title=The Mediterranean World in Late Antiquity: AD 395–700|date=29 April 2015|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-67305-4|language=en}}
* {{Cite web |title=LAKHMIDS – Encyclopaedia Iranica |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/lakhmids |access-date=18 December 2017 |website=Iranicaonline.org |language=en}}&lt;/ref&gt; Before the expansion of the [[Rashidun Caliphate]], the term &quot;Arab&quot; referred to any of the both largely nomadic and settled Arabic-speaking people from the Arabian Peninsula, the Syrian Desert, and [[Lower Mesopotamia]], with some even reaching what is now [[Upper Mesopotamia|northern Iraq]].&lt;ref&gt;* {{Cite web |date=2019 |title=Arab |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Arab |website=Encyclopædia Britannica |language=en |orig-year=1998}}
* {{cite book|last1=Grant|first1=Christina Phelps|title=The Syrian desert : caravans, travel and exploration|date=2003|publisher=Taylor and Francis|isbn=978-1-136-19271-5|location=Hoboken}}
