Arabs are a diverse group in terms of religious affiliations and practices. In the [[Pre-Islamic Arabia|pre-Islamic era]], most Arabs followed [[Polytheism|polytheistic]] religions. However, some tribes had adopted [[Christianity]] or [[Judaism]] and a few individuals, known as the ''[[hanif]]s'', apparently observed another form of [[monotheism]].&lt;ref name=&quot;auto&quot;&gt;* {{Cite book |last=Berkey, Jonathan Porter |url=https://archive.org/details/formationofislam0000berk |title=The Formation of Islam: Religion and Society in the Near East, 600–1800 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |year=2003 |isbn=978-0-521-58813-3 |page=[https://archive.org/details/formationofislam0000berk/page/42 42] |url-access=registration}}
* {{cite book|last1=Robinson|first1=Neal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2UL8AQAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA75|title=Islam: A Concise Introduction|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-81773-1|language=en}}&lt;/ref&gt; Presently, there is a sizable Christian minority in the Arab world.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web |date=4 April 2014 |title=Religious Diversity Around The World – Pew Research Center |url=http://www.pewforum.org/2014/04/04/global-religious-diversity/ |website=Pew Research Center's Religion &amp; Public Life Project}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[Arab Muslims]] primarily belong to the [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]], [[Shia Islam|Shia]], [[Ibadi Islam|Ibadi]], and [[Alawites|Alawite]] denominations. [[Arab Christians]] generally follow [[Eastern Christianity]], such as those within the [[Oriental Orthodox Churches]], the [[Eastern Catholic Churches]], or the [[Eastern Protestant Christianity|Eastern Protestant Churches]].&lt;ref name=&quot;PharesIntro&quot;&gt;*{{Cite web |last=Phares |first=Walid |author-link=Walid Phares |date=2001 |title=Arab Christians: An Introduction |url=https://www.arabicbible.com/for-christians/christians/1396-arab-christians-introduction.html |publisher=Arabic Bible Outreach Ministry}}
